;;; ============================================================
;;; 07-data-types
;;; strings, chars, vectors, bytevectors, pairs, lists
;;; ============================================================
;;;
;;; Regression tripwires for data types.  Each entry is pinned to a specific
;;; bug that was fixed -- this is NOT feature coverage.  Only Scheme-
;;; observable, non-spec regressions belong here; spec deviations go in
;;; R7RS-Compliance-Tests/, internal-only bugs in undercarriage gc_test.cpp.
;;; See 00-conventions.md for the full routing rule.
;;;
;;; HOW TO ADD A REGRESSION
;;;   - Append to the END of this file.  Tests run top-to-bottom; keep them
;;;     in chronological order (oldest bug first) so the file reads as a
;;;     timeline for this subsystem.
;;;   - Precede each case with a provenance comment so it stays meaningful:
;;;        ; REG <yyyy-mm-dd> -- <commit-or-issue> -- <one line: what broke>
;;;        ; Symptom: <what the user saw before the fix>
;;;   - Keep the reproducer MINIMAL, then give the expected result:
;;;        >>> (expression)
;;;        ==> expected             ; or:  %%% %any-error%
;;;
; REG 2026-06-18 (scar added; fix cpp 1af8bfd) -- string-set!/string-ref must be
;   indexed by code point, not by UTF-8 byte, across multibyte characters.
; Symptom: cppScheme2 indexed string storage by byte, so string-set!/string-ref
;   on a string containing a multibyte char (e.g. "aλb") addressed the wrong
;   element and could corrupt the encoding.  (pyScheme was natively correct.)
;   Asserted via code points so the expected value stays ASCII: λ = U+03BB = 955.
>>> (let ((s (string-copy "a\x3BB;b"))) (string-set! s 0 #\X) (list (string-length s) (char->integer (string-ref s 1)) (char->integer (string-ref s 0))))
... ; length stays 3 code points; index 1 is still λ (955); index 0 is now X (88)
==> (3 955 88)
